i/items/12337/relationships/content"}},"specialtyTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/specialtyTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/specialtyTags"}},"primaryTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/primaryTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/primaryTags"}},"contributionTypes":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/contributionTypes","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/contributionTypes"}},"contributors":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/contributors","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/contributors"}},"contribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/contribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/contribution"}},"myContribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/myContribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/myContribution"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"101960"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/activeRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/activeRevision"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1994"},{"type":"tags","id":"2030"},{"type":"tags","id":"4256"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4951"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"9623"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29367"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12337/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"120321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the general practice clinic with his parent for review of burns sustained yesterday evening. The parent reports the child climbed into a hot bath unsupervised before they\u0027d had time to check the temperature. There is no significant medical history and the child takes no regular medications. The child has attended on-time for their vaccinations since birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears to be in pain but is alert and interactive. His vital signs are within normal limits. There are well demarcated circumferential superficial partial thickness burns to both legs and lower abdomen extending from the umbilicus to the ankles with the skin on the buttocks appearing normal. There remainder of the examination is unremarkable. The child is given appropriate analgesia with good effect. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange second daily hydrogel dressings","Prescribe prophylactic antibiotics","Prescribe silver sulfadiazine cream","Place child under running cold water for 20 minutes","Notify child protection services"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents several concerning features highly suggestive of non-accidental injury. The burn pattern is characteristic of forced immersion, with circumferential burns showing clear demarcation lines and sparing of the buttocks and posterior thighs. This pattern occurs when a child is forcibly held in hot water while struggling to escape, with the buttocks being pressed against the base of the bath remaining protected. Additional concerning features in this case include the delay in seeking medical attention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENotify child protection services\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step. Detailed documentation of the injuries, including photographs if possible, and immediate notification of authorities is essential when child abuse is suspected. This ensures proper investigation and protection of the child while preserving evidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlace child under running cold water\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for an acute burn, but this presentation is delayed and first aid measures are no longer the priority. The suspicious nature of the injuries requires immediate reporting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribe prophylactic antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated for superficial partial thickness burns. While infection prevention is important in burn management, prophylactic antibiotics do not reduce infection rates and may promote antibiotic resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribe silver sulfadiazine cream\u003C/strong\u003E addresses only the burns management and ignores the underlying child protection concerns. While burn treatment is important, it should not precede mandatory reporting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange second daily hydrogel dressings\u003C/strong\u003E focuses solely on wound care when the priority is addressing the likely non-accidental injury and can be arranged after appropriate authorities have been notified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Circumferential burns with sparing of flexural surfaces suggest forced immersion and non-accidental injury.","Clear documentation of physical findings and concerns is essential in suspected child abuse cases.","Mandatory reporting to child protection services is required when there is reasonable suspicion of child abuse."],"references":["Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Clinical Practice Guidelines: Burns - assessment and management. Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/Burns/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"101960"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19567"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/120321/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"101960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101960"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-10-15T10:35:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-10-15T10:35:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12337"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101960/item","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101960/relationships/item"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"120321"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/101960/content","self":"https://app.emedici